    "# TF-IDF: Weighting Words by Informativeness\n",
    "\n",
    "## Motivation\n",
    "\n",
    "Bag of Words counts every word equally.\n",
    "But common words like *the*, *is*, and *and* appear everywhere and carry little discriminating information.\n",
    "\n",
    "**TF-IDF** (Term Frequency–Inverse Document Frequency) solves this by down-weighting terms that appear in many documents.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{TF-IDF}(t, d) = \\underbrace{\\frac{f_{t,d}}{\\sum_{t'} f_{t',d}}}_{\\text{Term Frequency}} \\times \\underbrace{\\log\\frac{N}{|\\{d : t \\in d\\}|}}_{\\text{Inverse Document Frequency}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $f_{t,d}$ is the count of term $t$ in document $d$, and $N$ is the total number of documents.\n",
    "\n",
    "Words that are **frequent in one document** but **rare across the corpus** receive high TF-IDF weight — these are the words that best characterize that document.\n",
    "\n",
    "## TF-IDF in Practice"
   ]
