    "\n",
    "## When to Use Bag of Words\n",
    "\n",
    "Use BoW when:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Data is small or medium  \n",
    "- Interpretability matters  \n",
    "- You need a fast baseline  \n",
    "\n",
    "Avoid BoW when:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Documents are long  \n",
    "- Semantic nuance matters  \n",
    "- Context is essential  \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Key Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "- Bag of Words is fundamentally about **counting**, not understanding  \n",
    "- It is a stepping stone to TF‑IDF, embeddings, and transformers  \n",
    "- Representation is the foundation of all NLP  \n",
    "- Generative and discriminative models offer complementary perspectives  \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## What's Next: From Representations to Language Models\n",
    "\n",
    "The representations developed in this lecture — BoW, TF-IDF, and MLP classifiers — treat text as *unordered* feature bags.\n",
    "Words have individual weights, but sequence and context remain invisible.\n",
    "\n",
    "In Module 2 we formalize **language as a probability distribution over sequences**.\n",
    "That shift — from classifying documents to predicting the next token — lays the mathematical foundation for everything from N-gram language models to the transformer-based architectures that power modern generative AI.\n",
